SIMPLE: gutter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gutter
<hw>Gut"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>gotere</ets>, OF. <ets>goutiere</ets>, F.
<ets>goutti⟦egrave⟧re</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>gote</ets>, <ets>goute</ets>,
drop, F. <ets>goutte</ets>, fr. L. <ets>gutta</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A channel at the eaves of a roof for conveying away
the rain; an eaves channel; an eaves trough.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small channel at the roadside or elsewhere, to
lead off surface water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Gutters</qex> running with ale.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any narrow channel or groove; <as>as, a
<ex>gutter</ex> formed by erosion in the vent of a gun from repeated
firing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bowling)</fld> <def>Either of two sunken channels
at either side of the bowling alley, leading directly to the sunken pit
behind the pins. Balls not thrown accurately at the pins will drop into
such a channel bypassing the pins, and resulting in a score of zero for
that bowl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gutter member</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>an
architectural member made by treating the outside face of the gutter in
a decorative fashion, or by crowning it with ornaments, regularly
spaced, like a diminutive battlement.</cd> -- <col><b>Gutter
plane</b></col>, <cd>a carpenter's plane with a rounded bottom for
planing out gutters.</cd> -- <col><b>Gutter snipe</b></col>, <cd>a
neglected boy running at large; a street Arab.</cd>
<mark>[Slang]</mark><-- also guttersnipe. --> -- <col><b>Gutter
stick</b></col> <fld>(Printing)</fld>, <cd>one of the pieces of
furniture which separate pages in a form.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gutter
<hw>Gut*ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Guttered</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Guttering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut or form into
small longitudinal hollows; to channel.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply with a gutter or gutters.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gutter
<hw>Gut"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become channeled, as a candle
when the flame flares in the wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gutter ball</ent>⟦br⟧
